  "texts": [
    "When the base judge assigns probabilities to its scores, we denote them by p. At inference time, when we judge, a human score is predicted from ϕ(e), along with b or p. At training time, we use ground-truth human scores to train the predictor and denote them by s. We show architectures of our quantitative judges in Figure 1 and present them next.",
    "The least-squares (LS) judge is an absolute judge that predicts the score of a single response as",
    "where ϕ(e) ∈ R d is the embedding of base judge's rationale, b ∈ R is its score, u ⊕ v represents a concatenated vector of u and v, θ ∈ R d+1 is a learned model parameter, and c is a population bias.",
    "The population bias plays the same role as the bias term in linear regression.",
    "We introduce b so that we can always learn a judge that performs at least as well as the base judge."
  ],
